KR1: Using @code_*¶

For this section, we will explore the @code_* macros and what they can tell about how Julia handles the codes we write.

@code_native¶

Following the Julia documentation, the function for the macro @code_native prints out the assembly instructions needed by Julia to run the function that is passed through it. We illustrate how it handles this with the following examples. The first cell runs the macro for the cos(x) function with input 0, while the second cell does the same but for input 0.0.

In [2]:
@code_native cos(0)

	.text
; ┌ @ math.jl:404 within `cos'
	pushq	%rax
; │ @ math.jl:405 within `cos'
; │┌ @ float.jl:206 within `float'
; ││┌ @ float.jl:191 within `AbstractFloat'
; │││┌ @ float.jl:94 within `Float64'
	vcvtsi2sd	%rdi, %xmm0, %xmm0
; │└└└
; │ @ math.jl:407 within `cos'
	movabsq	$cos, %rax
	callq	*%rax
	popq	%rax
	retq
	nopw	%cs:(%rax,%rax)
; └
In [3]:
@suppress @code_native cos(0.0);
#output suppressed to reduce filler text, remove @suppress to see full code

From here we can immediately see two distinct differences in the outputs. The most obvious one is the length, with cos(0.0) needing nearly ten times as many instructions to handle the operation as opposed to just cos(0). The second difference is in the modules used to call the cosine function. cos(0) calls its cosine function from the module math.jl, while cos(0.0) calls it from trig.jl. This implies that Julia can call different methods of the same function to efficiently handle certain arguments based on the type inferenced by the compiler.

@code_typed, @code_warntype, and @code_lowered¶

The function code_typed explicitly infers the type of the argument used by the function, then returns what is called an array of type inferred lowered forms of the methods which match the generic function being passed and the inferred argument type. In the following example, cos(x) is the generic function and 0 and 0.0 are the arguments being passed by cos(x). It is readily apparent that there are more processes involved when an (somewhat) explicit float is passed through the cos(x) function.

In [4]:
@code_typed cos(0)
Out[4]:
CodeInfo(
1 ─ %1 = Base.sitofp(Float64, x)::Float64
└──      goto #3 if not false
2 ─      nothing::Nothing
3 ┄ %4 = invoke Base.Math.cos(%1::Float64)::Float64
└──      return %4
) => Float64
In [5]:
@suppress @code_typed cos(0.0);
#output suppressed to reduce filler text, remove @suppress to see full code

code_warntype prints out the generic function name, all the types of the variables involved (not just the argument), and the abstract syntax tree of the method process. Its primary use is to check whether or not there is potential type instability as the process runs. In the case of the examples below, the inferred types are stated clearly and there is no risk for type instability. (Although type instability may not necessarily be a bad thing for Julia as long as it correctly infers its argument types.)

@code_llvm¶

Lastly, code_llvm prints out the LLVM instructions to Julia's Just-In-Time compiler in order to executre the code. We can clearly see here the difference in libraries and modules used depending on the inferred variable types passed to the function.

In [10]:
@code_llvm cos(0)

;  @ math.jl:404 within `cos'
define double @julia_cos_1908(i64 signext %0) {
top:
;  @ math.jl:405 within `cos'
; ┌ @ float.jl:206 within `float'
; │┌ @ float.jl:191 within `AbstractFloat'
; ││┌ @ float.jl:94 within `Float64'
     %1 = sitofp i64 %0 to double
; └└└
;  @ math.jl:407 within `cos'
  %2 = call double @j_cos_1910(double %1)
  ret double %2
}
In [11]:
@suppress @code_llvm cos(0.0);
#output suppressed to reduce filler text, remove @suppress to see full code

KR2: Julia constants¶

Here we will demonstrate the constant fixing of functions in Julia. Let us define a function g such that

In [12]:
g(x) = x*cos(pi/2)
Out[12]:
g (generic function with 1 method)

The function with name g is a generic function then containing a single method x*cos(pi/2). Doing a @code_warntype and @code_llvm check on this function gives us

In [13]:
@code_llvm g(pi/2)

;  @ In[12]:1 within `g'
define double @julia_g_1994(double %0) {
top:
; ┌ @ float.jl:332 within `*'
   %1 = fmul double %0, 0x3C91A62633145C07
; └
  ret double %1
}

The LLVM code made by @code_llvm shows that cos(pi/2) is already parsed as the constant 0x3C91A62633145C07 even before the code is passed to the compiler. We can see the difference by defining another function g_x and passing it through @code_llvm.

In [14]:
gₓ(x) = x*cos(x)
Out[14]:
gₓ (generic function with 1 method)
In [15]:
@code_llvm gₓ(pi/2)

;  @ In[14]:1 within `gₓ'
define double @"julia_g\E2\82\93_2020"(double %0) {
top:
  %1 = call double @j_cos_2022(double %0)
; ┌ @ float.jl:332 within `*'
   %2 = fmul double %1, %0
; └
  ret double %2
}

The LLVM output makes it clear that cos(x) is called and evaluated first before being multiplied to x. In this case, cos(x = pi/2) is not treated as a constant.

KR3: Type inference and multiple dispatch¶

Julia makes a distinction between functions and methods. As shown in passing in KR1, the cos(x) function itself is the generic function attached to multiple methods. These methods can change based on the inferred type of the argument x. We can demonstrate this by defining our own function xcosine.

In [16]:
xcosine(x) = x * cos(x)
xcosine(x::String) = "This is a string. Please input a number between -1 and 1."
xcosine(x::Char) = "This is a character. Please input a number between -1 and 1."
Out[16]:
xcosine (generic function with 3 methods)

xcosine(x) has three methods: a general method x * cos(x), and two other methods to accommodate for cases when the input x is either a string or a character. This sort of multiple dispatch is useful in catching cases where the wrong type of input may produce undesirable results.

For example, if we naively define some variable y::Char as an input to a function that only takes numerical arguments (such as cos(x)), we end up with the error below.

In [17]:
y = 'π'
y*cos(y)

MethodError: no method matching cos(::Char)
Closest candidates are:
  cos(::Float16) at math.jl:1159
  cos(::ComplexF16) at math.jl:1160
  cos(::Complex{T}) where T at complex.jl:849
  ...

Stacktrace:
 [1] top-level scope
   @ In[17]:2
 [2] eval
   @ ./boot.jl:360 [inlined]
 [3] include_string(mapexpr::typeof(REPL.softscope), mod::Module, code::String, filename::String)
   @ Base ./loading.jl:1116

For our function xcosine(x) with multiple dispatch cases however, it is able to handle string and character inputs as exceptions, and is able to output the appropriately defined methods.

In [18]:
xcosine(π)
Out[18]:
-3.141592653589793
In [19]:
xcosine("π")
Out[19]:
"This is a string. Please input a number between -1 and 1."
In [20]:
xcosine('π')
Out[20]:
"This is a character. Please input a number between -1 and 1."

KR4: my_sum(x) vs sum(x), benchmarked with @time¶

Below is the custom array summing function my_sum(x), which takes an array input and outputs the sum of all of its elements.

In [21]:
function my_sum(x)
    sum = zero(eltype(x)) #eltype ensures that zero() generates a zero of the same data type as elements of x
    for i in x
        sum += i
    end
    return sum
end
Out[21]:
my_sum (generic function with 1 method)

We can test out the efficiency of my_sum(x), we can try pass through it an array of 10,000,000 random numbers and see how fast it runs against Julia's built-in sum(x) function.

In [22]:
x = rand(10_000_000);
In [23]:
println("my_sum(x)")
@timev my_sum(x)
println("\nsum(x)")
@timev sum(x);

my_sum(x)
  0.018217 seconds (8.19 k allocations: 447.467 KiB, 38.52% compilation time)
elapsed time (ns): 18216666
bytes allocated:   458206
pool allocs:       8189

sum(x)
  0.032459 seconds (76.35 k allocations: 4.506 MiB, 87.22% compilation time)
elapsed time (ns): 32459034
bytes allocated:   4724681
pool allocs:       76350
non-pool GC allocs:4

On first pass, the my_sum(x) function we constructed runs almost twice as fast as the built-in function. This is mainly because of Julia's JIT features. The same features, however, will also make Julia's subsequent runs of the functions a lot faster, as we can see in the next cell.

In [24]:
println("my_sum(x)")
@timev my_sum(x)
println("\nsum(x)")
@timev sum(x);

my_sum(x)
  0.011841 seconds (1 allocation: 16 bytes)
elapsed time (ns): 11841465
bytes allocated:   16
pool allocs:       1

sum(x)
  0.004445 seconds (1 allocation: 16 bytes)
elapsed time (ns): 4445358
bytes allocated:   16
pool allocs:       1

As demonstrated, my_sum(x) does not benefit as much as sum(x) with the just-in-time compilation, likely because of some overhead we may have introduced in the code.

KR5: Plotting Mandelbrot in Julia¶

We can also use Julia to perform more complex calculations and visualizations, such as that of the Mandelbrot set. Here we use the Julia script plotMandelbrot.jl with functions mandebrot(c) (which checks if a complex number c is part of the Mandelbrot set) and plotMandelbrot(range; n = gridsize) (range is a tuple that defines the bounds of the grid, gridsize determines the number of points to plot on the grid). To see the script code, click here.

In [25]:
include("PlotMandelbrot.jl")
Out[25]:
plotMandelbrot (generic function with 2 methods)
In [26]:
plotMandelbrot((-1.0, 1.0); n = 1_000)
In [27]:
plotMandelbrot((-0.55, -0.5); n = 1_000)

KR6-7: Benchmarking Mandelbrot generation with @time macros¶

We can (sort of) measure the computational complexity of computing the membership within the Mandelbrot set by checking the computation time as a function of grid size. Let's try to plot the computation time against grid sizes $n = 10^1, 10^2, 10^3, 10^4$.

In [28]:
ngrids = [10, 
    10^2, 
    10^3, 
    10^4];
time = zeros(length(ngrids));
In [29]:
for i in 1:length(ngrids)
    time[i] = @elapsed plotMandelbrot((-1.0, 1.0); n = ngrids[i])
end
In [30]:
plot(ngrids, time, scale=:log10, label=false, xlabel="Number of grid points", ylabel="Elapsed time (in seconds)", 
    title="Mandelbrot plotting runtime")
Out[30]:

As we can see in the above plot, increasing the number of points by an order of magnitude increases the runtime by around three orders of magnitude (indeed, just running for $10^4$ points already took over 100 seconds). We use @elapsed for our timing implementation here as it directly gives the value of the runtime for each run of plotMandelbrot. Note as well that @elapsed does not return garbage collection time, only the pure run time of each run.
